[src:push-api/api-push-api] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:push-api/api-push-api] It’s been available across browsers since March 2023.
[src:push-api/api-push-api] The **Push API** gives web applications the ability to receive messages pushed to them from a server, whether or not the web app is in the foreground, or even currently loaded, on a user agent.
[src:push-api/api-push-api] This lets developers deliver asynchronous notifications and updates to users that opt in, resulting in better engagement with timely new content.
[src:push-api/api-push-api] For an app to receive push messages, it has to have an active service worker.
[src:push-api/api-push-api] When the service worker is active, it can subscribe to push notifications, using `PushManager.subscribe()`.
[src:push-api/api-push-api] The resulting `PushSubscription` includes all the information that the application needs to send a push message: an endpoint and the encryption key needed for sending data.
[src:push-api/api-push-api] The service worker will be started as necessary to handle incoming push messages, which are delivered to the `onpush` event handler.
[src:push-api/api-push-api] Each subscription is unique to a service worker.
[src:push-api/api-push-api] The endpoint for the subscription is a unique capability URL: knowledge of the endpoint is all that is necessary to send a message to your application.
[src:push-api/api-push-api] The endpoint URL therefore needs to be kept secret, or other applications might be able to send push messages to your application.
[src:push-api/api-push-api] Activating a service worker to deliver a push message can result in increased resource usage, particularly of the battery.
[src:push-api/api-push-api] Different browsers have different schemes for handling this, there is currently no standard mechanism.
[src:push-api/api-push-api] Firefox allows a limited number (quota) of push messages to be sent to an application, although Push messages that generate notifications are exempt from this limit.
[src:push-api/api-push-api] The limit is refreshed each time the site is visited.
[src:push-api/api-push-api] Represents a push action, sent to the global scope of a `ServiceWorker`.
[src:push-api/api-push-api] It contains information sent from an application to a `PushSubscription`.
[src:push-api/api-push-api] Provides a way to receive notifications from third-party servers, as well as request URLs for push notifications.
[src:push-api/api-push-api] Provides access to push data sent by a server, and includes methods to manipulate the received data.
[src:push-api/api-push-api] Provides a subscription's URL endpoint, and allows unsubscribing from a push service.
[src:push-api/api-push-api] Represents the options associated with the push subscription.
[src:push-api/api-push-api] The following additions to the Service Worker API have been specified in the Push API spec to provide an entry point for using Push messages.
[src:push-api/api-push-api] They also monitor and respond to push and subscription change events.
[src:push-api/api-push-api] Returns a reference to the `PushManager` interface for managing push subscriptions including subscribing, getting an active subscription, and accessing push permission status.
[src:push-api/api-push-api] This is the entry point into using Push messaging.
[src:push-api/api-push-api] An event handler fired whenever a `push` event occurs; that is, whenever a server push message is received.
[src:push-api/api-push-api] Mozilla's ServiceWorker Cookbook contains many useful Push examples.
[src:push-api/api-pushevent] The **`PushEvent`** interface of the Push API represents a push message that has been received.
[src:push-api/api-pushevent] This event is sent to the global scope of a `ServiceWorker`.
[src:push-api/api-pushevent] It contains the information sent from an application server to a `PushSubscription`.
[src:push-api/api-pushevent] Returns a reference to a `PushMessageData` object containing data sent to the `PushSubscription`.
[src:push-api/api-pushevent] The following example takes data from a `PushEvent` and displays it on all of the service worker's clients.
[src:push-api/api-pushmanager] The **`PushManager`** interface of the Push API provides a way to receive notifications from third-party servers as well as request URLs for push notifications.
[src:push-api/api-pushmanager] This interface is accessed via the `ServiceWorkerRegistration.pushManager` property.
[src:push-api/api-pushmanager] Returns an array of supported content codings that can be used to encrypt the payload of a push message.
[src:push-api/api-pushmanager] Retrieves an existing push subscription.
[src:push-api/api-pushmanager] It returns a `Promise` that resolves to a `PushSubscription` object containing details of an existing subscription.
[src:push-api/api-pushmanager] If no existing subscription exists, this resolves to a `null` value.
[src:push-api/api-pushmanager] Returns a `Promise` that resolves to the permission state of the current `PushManager`, which will be one of `'granted'`, `'denied'`, or `'prompt'`.
[src:push-api/api-pushmanager] It returns a `Promise` that resolves to a `PushSubscription` object containing details of a push subscription.
[src:push-api/api-pushmanager] A new push subscription is created if the current service worker does not have an existing subscription.
[src:push-api/api-pushmanager] Returns a `Promise` that resolves to the `PushPermissionStatus` of the requesting webapp, which will be one of `granted`, `denied`, or `default`.
[src:push-api/api-pushmanager] Replaced by `PushManager.permissionState()`.
[src:push-api/api-pushmanager] Replaced by `PushManager.getSubscription()`.
[src:push-api/api-pushmanager] Unregisters and deletes a specified subscription endpoint.
[src:push-api/api-pushmanager] In the updated API, a subscription is unregistered by calling the `PushSubscription.unsubscribe()` method.
[src:push-api/push-technology] In push technology, clients can express their preferences for certain types of information or data, typically through a process known as the publish–subscribe model.
[src:push-api/push-technology] In this model, a client "subscribes" to specific information channels hosted by a server.
[src:push-api/push-technology] When new content becomes available on these channels, the server automatically sends, or "pushes," this information to the subscribed client.
[src:push-api/push-technology] Under certain conditions, such as restrictive security policies that block incoming HTTP requests, push technology is sometimes simulated using a technique called polling.
[src:push-api/push-technology] In these cases, the client periodically checks with the server to see if new information is available, rather than receiving automatic updates.
[src:push-api/push-technology] Synchronous conferencing and instant messaging are examples of push services.
[src:push-api/push-technology] Chat messages and sometimes files are pushed to the user as soon as they are received by the messaging service.
[src:push-api/push-technology] Both decentralized peer-to-peer programs (such as WASTE) and centralized programs (such as IRC or XMPP) allow pushing files, which means the sender initiates the data transfer rather than the recipient.
[src:push-api/push-technology] Email may also be a push system: SMTP is a push protocol (see Push e-mail).
[src:push-api/push-technology] However, the last step—from mail server to desktop computer—typically uses a pull protocol like POP3 or IMAP.
[src:push-api/push-technology] Modern e-mail clients make this step seem instantaneous by repeatedly polling the mail server, frequently checking it for new mail.
[src:push-api/push-technology] The IMAP protocol includes the IDLE command, which allows the server to tell the client when new messages arrive.
[src:push-api/push-technology] The original BlackBerry was the first popular example of push-email in a wireless context.
[src:push-api/push-technology] Another example is the PointCast Network, which was widely covered in the 1990s.
[src:push-api/push-technology] It delivered news and stock market data as a screensaver.
[src:push-api/push-technology] Both Netscape and Microsoft integrated push technology through the Channel Definition Format (CDF) into their software at the height of the browser wars, but it was never very popular.
[src:push-api/push-technology] Other uses of push-enabled web applications include software updates distribution ("push updates"), market data distribution (stock tickers), online chat/messaging systems (webchat), auctions, online betting and gaming, sport results, monitoring consoles, and sensor network monitoring.
[src:push-api/push-technology] The Web push proposal of the Internet Engineering Task Force is a simple protocol using HTTP version 2 to deliver real-time events, such as incoming calls or messages, which can be delivered (or "pushed") in a timely fashion.
[src:push-api/push-technology] The protocol consolidates all real-time events into a single session which ensures more efficient use of network and radio resources.
[src:push-api/push-technology] A single service consolidates all events, distributing those events to applications as they arrive.
[src:push-api/push-technology] This requires just one session, avoiding duplicated overhead costs.
[src:push-api/push-technology] Web Notifications are part of the W3C standard and define an API for end-user notifications.
[src:push-api/push-technology] A notification allows alerting the user of an event, such as the delivery of an email, outside the context of a web page.
[src:push-api/push-technology] As part of this standard, Push API is fully implemented in Chrome, Firefox, and Edge, and partially implemented in Safari as of February 2023.
[src:push-api/push-technology] HTTP server push (also known as HTTP streaming) is a mechanism for sending unsolicited (asynchronous) data from a web server to a web browser.
[src:push-api/push-technology] HTTP server push can be achieved through any of several mechanisms.
[src:push-api/push-technology] As a part of HTML5 the Web Socket API allows a web server and client to communicate over a full-duplex TCP connection.
[src:push-api/push-technology] Generally, the web server does not terminate a connection after response data has been served to a client.
[src:push-api/push-technology] The web server leaves the connection open so that if an event occurs (for example, a change in internal data which needs to be reported to one or multiple clients), it can be sent out immediately; otherwise, the event would have to be queued until the client's next request is received.
[src:push-api/push-technology] Most web servers offer this functionality via CGI (e.g., Non-Parsed Headers scripts on Apache HTTP Server).
[src:push-api/push-technology] The underlying mechanism for this approach is chunked transfer encoding.
[src:push-api/push-technology] Another mechanism is related to a special MIME type called `multipart/x-mixed-replace`, which was introduced by Netscape in 1995.
[src:push-api/push-technology] Web browsers interpret this as a document that changes whenever the server pushes a new version to the client.
[src:push-api/push-technology] It is still supported by Firefox, Opera, and Safari today, but it is ignored by Internet Explorer and is only partially supported by Chrome.
[src:push-api/push-technology] It can be applied to HTML documents, and also for streaming images in webcam applications.
[src:push-api/push-technology] The WHATWG Web Applications 1.0 proposal includes a mechanism to push content to the client.
[src:push-api/push-technology] On September 1, 2006, the Opera web browser implemented this new experimental system in a feature called "Server-Sent Events".
[src:push-api/push-technology] In this technique, the server takes advantage of persistent HTTP connections, leaving the response perpetually "open" (i.e., the server never terminates the response), effectively fooling the browser to remain in "loading" mode after the initial page load could be considered complete.
[src:push-api/push-technology] The server then periodically sends snippets of JavaScript to update the content of the page, thereby achieving push capability.
[src:push-api/push-technology] By using this technique, the client doesn't need Java applets or other plug-ins in order to keep an open connection to the server; the client is automatically notified about new events, pushed by the server.
[src:push-api/push-technology] One serious drawback to this method, however, is the lack of control the server has over the browser timing out; a page refresh is always necessary if a timeout occurs on the browser end.
[src:push-api/push-technology] Long polling is itself not a true push; long polling is a variation of the traditional polling technique, but it allows emulating a push mechanism under circumstances where a real push is not possible, such as sites with security policies that require rejection of incoming HTTP requests.
[src:push-api/push-technology] With long polling, the client requests to get more information from the server exactly as in normal polling, but with the expectation that the server may not respond immediately.
[src:push-api/push-technology] If the server has no new information for the client when the poll is received, then instead of sending an empty response, the server holds the request open and waits for response information to become available.
[src:push-api/push-technology] Once it does have new information, the server immediately sends an HTTP response to the client, completing the open HTTP request.
[src:push-api/push-technology] Upon receipt of the server response, the client often immediately issues another server request.
[src:push-api/push-technology] In this way the usual response latency (the time between when the information first becomes available and the next client request) otherwise associated with polling clients is eliminated.
[src:push-api/push-technology] This technique, used by chat applications, makes use of the XML Socket object in a single-pixel Adobe Flash movie.
[src:push-api/push-technology] Under the control of JavaScript, the client establishes a TCP connection to a unidirectional relay on the server.
[src:push-api/push-technology] The relay server does not read anything from this socket; instead, it immediately sends the client a unique identifier.
[src:push-api/push-technology] Next, the client makes an HTTP request to the web server, including this identifier with it.
[src:push-api/push-technology] The web application can then push messages addressed to the client to a local interface of the relay server, which relays them over the Flash socket.
[src:push-api/push-technology] The advantage of this approach is that it appreciates the natural read-write asymmetry that is typical of many web applications, including chat, and as a consequence it offers high efficiency.
[src:push-api/push-technology] Since it does not accept data on outgoing sockets, the relay server does not need to poll outgoing TCP connections *at all*, making it possible to hold open tens of thousands of concurrent connections.
[src:push-api/push-technology] In this model, the limit to scale is the TCP stack of the underlying server operating system.
[src:push-api/push-technology] In services such as cloud computing, to increase reliability and availability of data, it is usually pushed (replicated) to several machines.
[src:push-api/push-technology] For example, the Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS) makes 2 extra copies of any object stored.
[src:push-api/push-technology] RGDD focuses on efficiently casting an object from one location to many while saving bandwidth by sending minimal number of copies (only one in the best case) of the object over any link across the network.
[src:push-api/push-technology] For example, Datacast is a scheme for delivery to many nodes inside data centers that relies on regular and structured topologies and DCCast is a similar approach for delivery across data centers.
[src:push-api/push-technology] A push notification is a message that is "pushed" from a back-end server or application to a user interface, e.g. mobile applications or desktop applications.
[src:push-api/push-technology] Apple introduced push notifications for iPhone in 2009, and in 2010 Google released "Google Cloud to Device Messaging" (superseded by Google Cloud Messaging and then by Firebase Cloud Messaging).
[src:push-api/push-technology] Push notifications are mainly divided into two approaches, local notifications and remote notifications.
[src:push-api/push-technology] For local notifications, the application schedules the notification with the local device's OS.
[src:push-api/push-technology] The application sets a timer in the application itself, provided it is able to continuously run in the background.
[src:push-api/push-technology] When the event's scheduled time is reached, or the event's programmed condition is met, the message is displayed in the application's user interface.
[src:push-api/push-technology] Remote notifications are handled by a remote server.
[src:push-api/push-technology] Under this scenario, the client application needs to be registered on the server with a unique key (e.g., a UUID or Apple *Device Token*).
[src:push-api/push-technology] The server then transmits the message against the unique key to deliver it to the client via an agreed client/server protocol such as HTTP or XMPP.
[src:push-api/push-technology] When the push notification arrives at the client, it can cause the display of short notifications or messages, set badges on application icons, blink or continuously light up the notification LED, or play alert sounds to attract user's attention.
[src:push-api/push-technology] Push notifications are usually used by applications to bring information to users' attention.
[src:push-api/push-technology] Real-time push notifications may raise privacy issues since they can be used to bind virtual identities of social network pseudonyms to the real identities of the smartphone owners.
[src:push-api/push-technology] The use of unnecessary push notifications for promotional purposes has been criticized as an example of attention theft.
[src:push-api/pushsubscription] The `PushSubscription` interface of the Push API provides a subscription's URL endpoint along with the public key and secrets that should be used for encrypting push messages to this subscription.
[src:push-api/pushsubscription] This information must be passed to the application server, using any desired application-specific method.
[src:push-api/pushsubscription] The interface also provides information about when the subscription will expire, and a method to unsubscribe from the subscription.
[src:push-api/pushsubscription] A string containing the endpoint associated with the push subscription.
[src:push-api/pushsubscription] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` of the subscription expiration time associated with the push subscription, if there is one, or null otherwise.
[src:push-api/pushsubscription] An object containing the options used to create the subscription.
[src:push-api/pushsubscription] A string containing the subscription ID associated with the push subscription.
[src:push-api/pushsubscription] Returns an `ArrayBuffer` which contains the client's public key, which can then be sent to a server and used in encrypting push message data.
[src:push-api/pushsubscription] Standard serializer — returns a JSON representation of the subscription properties.
[src:push-api/pushsubscription] Starts the asynchronous process of unsubscribing from the push service, returning a `Promise` that resolves to a boolean value when the current subscription is successfully unregistered.
[src:push-api/pushsubscription] Each browser uses a particular push service.
[src:push-api/pushsubscription] A service worker can use `PushManager.subscribe()` to subscribe to the supported service, and use the returned `PushSubscription` to discover the endpoint where push messages should be sent.
[src:push-api/pushsubscription] The `PushSubscription` is also used to get the public key and secret that the application server must use to encrypt the messages that it sends to the push service.
[src:push-api/pushsubscription] Note that the private keys used to decrypt push messages are not shared by the browser, and are used to decrypt messages before they are passed to the service worker.
[src:push-api/pushsubscription] This ensures that push messages remain private as they pass through the push server infrastructure.
[src:push-api/pushsubscription] The service worker doesn't need to know anything about the endpoints or encryption, other than to pass the relevant information onto the application server.
[src:push-api/pushsubscription] Any mechanism may be used to share the information with the application server.
[src:push-api/pushsubscription] The `p256dh` public key and `auth` secret used for encrypting the message are provided to the service worker via its push subscription, using the `PushSubscription.getKey()` method, along with the target endpoint for sending push messages in `PushSubscription.endpoint`.
[src:push-api/pushsubscription] The coding that should be used for encryption is provided by the `PushManager.supportedContentEncodings` static property.
[src:push-api/pushsubscription] This example shows how you might put the needed information from `PushSubscription` and `supportedContentEncodings` into a JSON object, serialize it using `JSON.stringify()`, and post the result to the application server.
[src:push-api/serviceworkerregistration-pushmanager] The **`pushManager`** read-only property of the `ServiceWorkerRegistration` interface returns a reference to the `PushManager` interface for managing push subscriptions; this includes support for subscribing, getting an active subscription, and accessing push permission status.
[src:push-api/websocket] WebSocket is distinct from HTTP used to serve most webpages.
[src:push-api/websocket] Although they are different, RFC 6455 states that WebSocket "is designed to work over HTTP ports 443 and 80 as well as to support HTTP proxies and intermediaries", making the WebSocket protocol compatible with HTTP.
[src:push-api/websocket] To achieve compatibility, the WebSocket handshake uses the HTTP Upgrade header to change from the HTTP protocol to the WebSocket protocol.
[src:push-api/websocket] The WebSocket protocol enables full-duplex interaction between a web browser (or other client application) and a web server with lower overhead than half-duplex alternatives such as HTTP polling, facilitating real-time data transfer from and to the server.
[src:push-api/websocket] This is achieved by providing a standardized way for the server to send content to the client without being first requested by the client, and allowing messages to be exchanged while keeping the connection open.
[src:push-api/websocket] In this way, a two-way ongoing conversation can take place between the client and the server.
[src:push-api/websocket] The communications are usually done over TCP port number 443 (or 80 in the case of unsecured connections), which is beneficial for environments that block non-web Internet connections using a firewall.
[src:push-api/websocket] Additionally, WebSocket enables streams of messages on top of TCP.
[src:push-api/websocket] TCP alone deals with streams of bytes with no inherent concept of a message.
[src:push-api/websocket] Similar two-way browser–server communications have been achieved in non-standardized ways using stopgap technologies such as Comet or Adobe Flash Player.
[src:push-api/websocket] Most browsers support the protocol, including Google Chrome, Firefox, Microsoft Edge, Internet Explorer, Safari and Opera.
[src:push-api/websocket] The WebSocket protocol specification defines `ws` (WebSocket) and `wss` (WebSocket Secure) as two new uniform resource identifier (URI) schemes that are used for unencrypted and encrypted connections respectively.
[src:push-api/websocket] Apart from the scheme name and fragment (i.e.
[src:push-api/websocket] `#` is not supported), the rest of the URI components are defined to use URI generic syntax.
[src:push-api/websocket] WebSocket was first referenced as TCPConnection in the HTML5 specification, as a placeholder for a TCP-based socket API.
[src:push-api/websocket] In June 2008, a series of discussions were led by Michael Carter that resulted in the first version of the protocol known as WebSocket.
[src:push-api/websocket] Before WebSocket, port 80 full-duplex communication was attainable using Comet channels; however, Comet implementation is nontrivial, and due to the TCP handshake and HTTP header overhead, it is inefficient for small messages.
[src:push-api/websocket] The WebSocket protocol aims to solve these problems without compromising the security assumptions of the web.
[src:push-api/websocket] The name "WebSocket" was coined by Ian Hickson and Michael Carter shortly thereafter through collaboration on the #whatwg IRC chat room, and subsequently authored for inclusion in the HTML5 specification by Ian Hickson.
[src:push-api/websocket] In December 2009, Google Chrome 4 was the first browser to ship full support for the standard, with WebSocket enabled by default.
[src:push-api/websocket] Development of the WebSocket protocol was subsequently moved from the W3C and WHATWG group to the IETF in February 2010, and authored for two revisions under Ian Hickson.
[src:push-api/websocket] After the protocol was shipped and enabled by default in multiple browsers, the RFC 6455 was finalized under Ian Fette in December 2011.
[src:push-api/websocket] RFC 7692 introduced compression extension to WebSocket using the DEFLATE algorithm on a per-message basis.
[src:push-api/websocket] A web application (e.g. web browser) may use the `WebSocket` interface to maintain bidirectional communications with a WebSocket server.
[src:push-api/websocket] **Frame-based message** exchange: data, ping and pong messages.
[src:push-api/websocket] **Closing handshake**: close message (request then echoed in response).
[src:push-api/websocket] The client sends an **HTTP request** (**method** **GET**, **version ≥ 1.1**) and the server returns an **HTTP response** with **status code 101** (*Switching Protocols*) on success.
[src:push-api/websocket] HTTP and WebSocket clients can connect to a server using the same port because the opening handshake uses HTTP.
[src:push-api/websocket] Sending additional HTTP headers (that are not in the table below) is allowed.
[src:push-api/websocket] After the *Switching Protocols* HTTP response, the opening handshake is complete, the HTTP protocol stops being used, and communication switches to a binary frame-based protocol.
[src:push-api/websocket] The following Python code generates a random `Sec-WebSocket-Key`.
[src:push-api/websocket] The following Python code calculates `Sec-WebSocket-Accept` using `Sec-WebSocket-Key` from the example request above.
[src:push-api/websocket] `Sec-WebSocket-Key` and `Sec-WebSocket-Accept` are intended to prevent a caching proxy from re-sending a previous WebSocket conversation, and does not provide any authentication, privacy, or integrity.
[src:push-api/websocket] Though some servers accept a short `Sec-WebSocket-Key`, many modern servers will reject the request with error "invalid Sec-WebSocket-Key header".
[src:push-api/websocket] After the opening handshake, the client and server can, at any time, send **data messages** (text or binary) and **control messages** (*Close*, *Ping*, *Pong*) to each other.
[src:push-api/websocket] A message is composed of **one frame if unfragmented** or **at least two frames if fragmented**.
[src:push-api/websocket] A **client must mask** all frames sent to the server.
[src:push-api/websocket] A **server must not mask** any frames sent to the client.
[src:push-api/websocket] Frame masking applies **XOR between the payload and the masking key**.
[src:push-api/websocket] The following pseudocode describes the algorithm used to both mask and unmask a frame.
[src:push-api/websocket] The `permessage-deflate` extension allows data messages to be compressed using the DEFLATE algorithm.
[src:push-api/websocket] For example, during the opening handshake, the client and server may use the following header to enable the extension.
[src:push-api/websocket] The `RSV1` field of the first frame of a data message must be set to indicate the payload data is compressed.
[src:push-api/websocket] Note: `recv()` returns up to the amount of bytes requested.
[src:push-api/websocket] For readability, the code ignores that, thus it may fail in non-ideal network conditions.
[src:push-api/websocket] A secure version of the WebSocket protocol is implemented in Firefox 6, Safari 6, Google Chrome 14, Opera 12.10 and Internet Explorer 10.
[src:push-api/websocket] A detailed protocol test suite report lists the conformance of those browsers to specific protocol aspects.
[src:push-api/websocket] An older, less secure version of the protocol was implemented in Opera 11 and Safari 5, as well as the mobile version of Safari in iOS 4.2.
[src:push-api/websocket] The BlackBerry Browser in OS7 implements WebSockets.
[src:push-api/websocket] Because of vulnerabilities, it was disabled in Firefox 4 and 5, and Opera 11.
[src:push-api/websocket] Using browser developer tools, developers can inspect the WebSocket handshake as well as the WebSocket frames.
[src:push-api/websocket] ASP.NET Core have support for WebSockets using the `app.UseWebSockets();` middleware.
[src:push-api/websocket] Unlike regular cross-domain HTTP requests, WebSocket requests are not restricted by the same-origin policy.
[src:push-api/websocket] It is better to use tokens or similar protection mechanisms to authenticate the WebSocket connection when sensitive (private) data is being transferred over the WebSocket.
[src:push-api/websocket] A live example of vulnerability was seen in 2020 in the form of Cable Haunt.
[src:push-api/websocket] WebSocket protocol client implementations try to detect whether the user agent is configured to use a proxy when connecting to destination host and port, and if it is, uses HTTP CONNECT method to set up a persistent tunnel.
[src:push-api/websocket] The WebSocket protocol is unaware of proxy servers and firewalls.
[src:push-api/websocket] Some proxy servers are transparent and work fine with WebSocket; others will prevent WebSocket from working correctly, causing the connection to fail.
[src:push-api/websocket] In some cases, additional proxy-server configuration may be required, and certain proxy servers may need to be upgraded to support WebSocket.
[src:push-api/websocket] If unencrypted WebSocket traffic flows through an explicit or a transparent proxy server without WebSockets support, the connection will likely fail.
[src:push-api/websocket] If an encrypted WebSocket connection is used, then the use of Transport Layer Security (TLS) in the WebSocket Secure connection ensures that an `HTTP CONNECT` command is issued when the browser is configured to use an explicit proxy server.
[src:push-api/websocket] This sets up a tunnel, which provides low-level end-to-end TCP communication through the HTTP proxy, between the WebSocket Secure client and the WebSocket server.
[src:push-api/websocket] In the case of transparent proxy servers, the browser is unaware of the proxy server, so no `HTTP CONNECT` is sent.
[src:push-api/websocket] However, since the wire traffic is encrypted, intermediate transparent proxy servers may simply allow the encrypted traffic through, so there is a much better chance that the WebSocket connection will succeed if WebSocket Secure is used.
[src:push-api/websocket] Using encryption is not free of resource cost, but often provides the highest success rate, since it would be travelling through a secure tunnel.
[src:push-api/websocket] A mid-2010 draft (version hixie-76) broke compatibility with reverse proxies and gateways by including eight bytes of key data after the headers, but not advertising that data in a `Content-Length: 8` header.
[src:push-api/websocket] This data was not forwarded by all intermediates, which could lead to protocol failure.
[src:push-api/websocket] More recent drafts (e.g., hybi-09) put the key data in a `Sec-WebSocket-Key` header, solving this problem.
